Does biodiversity affect ecosystem function?

Cedar Creek Reserve, Minnesota

Does higher plant biodiversity affect ecosystem stability?

Tilman et al. (2006) seeded 161 plots (9 x 9m) with varying numbers of plant species (1, 2, 4, 8, 16).

Plant species were assigned randomly to plots (18 possible species).

After 10 years of maintenance and measurement, researchers measured the stability of plant biomass production for each plot:

\[ \begin{aligned} \text{Biomass stability} = \frac{\bar{x}_\text{biomass}}{s_\text{biomass over 10 years}} \\ \end{aligned} \]

Load the data

# Set the web address where R will look for files from this repository
repo_url <- "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/elahi/xdp/master/data/"
dat <- read_csv(paste(repo_url, 
                      "chap17e3PlantDiversityAndStabilityRaw.csv", 
                      sep = ""))

Log transformation

Transformation: rescaling of data using a function

When observations are skewed so strongly that the details are obscured, we often apply a (natural) log transformation.

This transformation can be applied to independent or dependent variables.

Beware: can't log a negative value (add 1 or other small amount to all observations)

dat <- dat %>% 
  mutate(stability_log = log(biomassStability)) # natural log (base e)
dat

Check assumptions

Linearity

  • plot residuals against fitted values, should be scattered around 0

Normally distributed residuals

  • plot histogram of residuals or QQ plot

Residuals display constant variance (homoscedasticity)

  • plot residuals against fitted values, should be scattered around 0

Independence of residuals (i.e., observations)

  • often violated in time / space / phylogeny

Plot residuals vs fitted values

ggplot(data = fit1, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(x = "Fitted values", y = "Residuals")

Plot residuals: histogram

ggplot(data = fit1, aes(x = .resid)) + 
  geom_histogram()

Confidence vs prediction intervals

newdata <- data.frame(nSpecies = seq(1, 16, by = 1))

df_prediction <- predict(fit2, newdata, interval = "predict") %>%
  data.frame() %>% 
  mutate(nSpecies = seq(1, 16, by = 1))

df_confidence <- predict(fit2, newdata, interval = "confidence") %>%
  data.frame() %>% 
  mutate(nSpecies = seq(1, 16, by = 1))

dat %>% 
  ggplot(aes(nSpecies, stability_log)) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) + 
  geom_line(data = df_prediction, aes(x = nSpecies, y = lwr), 
            linetype = "dashed") + 
  geom_line(data = df_prediction, aes(x = nSpecies, y = upr), 
            linetype = "dashed") + 
  geom_line(data = df_confidence, aes(x = nSpecies, y = lwr), 
            linetype = "dashed") + 
  geom_line(data = df_confidence, aes(x = nSpecies, y = upr), 
            linetype = "dashed")

  • logit transformation
  • log(p / (1-p))
